With the integration of TSB, the deployment of Gravity, and Brazil earnings normalizing, we see a path to \(18 - 19\%\) ROTE; this could increase by \(>100bp\) if US Retail profitability is addressed. We raise our earnings \(7 - 8\%\) . On 1.3x TBV, with up to \(9\%\) upside to consensus EPS, we reiterate our Overweight.

We believe the CMD in February could target \(>18\%\) ROTE. With the capital fixed and the excess redeployed, we believe leveraging Santander's global platform and normalization of earnings in Brazil will drive the next leg of earnings growth. We see \(18 - 19\%\) ROTE 2028E, which we estimate could increase closer to \(20\%\) ROTE if the lack of profitability of the US Retail bank is addressed.

We raise our earnings \(7 - 8\%\) in 2026/27E. We incorporate TSB into our numbers as the proposed transaction has now been approved by Sabadell's EGM. We assume \(50\%\) of the costs of TSB are taken out, broadly in line with management targets; however, we believe the deployment of the core system 'Gravity' provides potential for more and would offset risk of revenue attrition. For the group, we now forecast the cost to income ratio to be 100bp lower than consensus.

Brazil is a key beneficiary of lower Fed rates. In a region where Santander makes the majority of its money via consumer lending, a \(15\%\) SELIC rate is depressing NII, and provisions remain elevated. However, with a more dovish Fed, our Latam economists see rate cuts starting in Q1 2026 or earlier, which should drive a recovery in earnings. We forecast ROTE improving from \(15\%\) to \(17.5\%\) in 2026 in the middle of its 10- year range, and we see upside potential in 2027/28 if economic policy turns more pro- market.

Fixing US Retail would provide further upside. Based on Santander's local reporting, its retail operations in the US have a C/I ratio of c. \(90\%\) . With Openbank US now up and refining locally and some of the previous regulatory restrictions cleared, we believe more decisive action is now possible. We estimate Retail & Commercial in the US (largely the old Sovereign bank) is a c. 14Obp drag on group C/I ratio and c. 130bp on ROTE; addressing this could raise the group ROTE closer to \(20\%\) not included in our base case.

We increase our total payout estimate to \(70\%\) 2025- 2028E. We believe the \(50\%\) ordinary payout policy will remain in place; however, with a \(4.6\%\) RWA CAGR, SAN could afford to pay out \(70\%\) of earnings. This makes up a total of \(>€40bn\) distribution between dividends and buybacks for the remainder of 2025 and out to 2028E, or a \(9 - 10\%\) annual yield. With the stock trading on \(8.3x\) PE 2026 vs. the sector on \(9.5x\) , for a \(13\%\) CAGR 2024- 2027E, we re- iterate our Overweight on the stock and keep it a Top Pick.

Fixing the capital level at Santander is largely behind the outperformance of the stock YTD. The disposal of Poland and re- redeployment of the capital generated via TSB/ additional buybacks have also driven earnings upgrades, as well as a helpful simplification of the business. We believe there is more to go. We think the cost performance is underappreciated, and Brazil is currently underearning, which, among other factors, leaves our base case numbers \(9\%\) ahead of consensus in 2027E. We estimate that Santander could afford to pay out \(70\%\) of the earnings, also above consensus. Additionally, addressing US Retail profitability more decisively is now more plausible, and has the potential to increase earnings further, closer to \(20\%\) ROTE, we calculate, which we do not include in our base case. On \(1.35x\) TBV, we remain Overweight and keep Santander as one of our European Top Picks.

We believe that the deployment of Santander's new core system, Gravity, has not been properly captured in consensus numbers. Our work benchmarking Santander's cost base shows a superior Cost- Income ratio in key regions driven by costs, and we believe the differential can improve further as the Gravity platform is rolled out globally, which should allow costs in Retail and Consumer to stay largely flat (see Santander: A Refocussed Footprint (13 May 2025)). The UK is a good illustration of this, where Santander has a \(54\%\) C/2025E vs. the sector at \(54.5\%\) , despite being largely a mortgage bank, with its NIM almost one- third lower than Lloyds for example.

Once TSB has been integrated, the gap will increase further, and we also see room for more cost cutting in the US and Mexico. For TSB, we assume \(50\%\) cost synergies, on top of the additional £200mn cost cutting planned in the UK on a standalone basis, which we already have in our numbers. Combined, we get to \(15\%\) ROTE for SAN UK in 2027- 28E, driven by an improvement in the cost to income ratio from \(56\%\) 2024 to \(47\%\) in 2028E. For the group as a whole, we reach a C/I ratio of \(39.3\%\) in 2028E vs. consensus at \(40.3\%\) .

We see c. \(15\%\) earnings growth the next 3 years... Brazil has been a source of push-back since we upgraded the stock in November; however, so far the economy is holding up better than expected, and we see upside into 2026/27E. In a region where Santander makes the majority of its money via consumer lending, a \(15\%\) SELIC rate is depressing NII and increasing provisions. However, a weaker dollar is reining in inflation expectations, and this should allow rate cuts starting in Q1 2026, in our Latam economists' view, or even earlier. After two quarters of better NII performance vs. expectations, we believe NII could accelerate to \(10\%\) growth in 2026- 2028E, and the Cost of Risk estimates - at \(5\%\) this year - have room to come down. Combined, we estimate ROTE to improve from \(15\%\) this year to \(17.5 - 18.6\%\) in 2026- 28E vs. a 10 year range of \(15 - 20\%\) .

... and we see a positive risk-reward into October 2026 elections. From a macro perspective, the key focus in Brazil is the budget deficit, expected to be at \(9\%\) this year (- \(0.5\%\) primary budget). With growth surprising positively and the SELIC rate at \(15\%\) , our economists believe there is room to manage the deficit to a more sustainable trajectory, which is key to improving the CoE in the region. Itau and Bradesco, Santander Brazil's closest peers (both covered by Jorge Kuri), have traded at a \(6.6 - 10.5x\) PE range over the last 25 years, based on consensus 1 yr forward PE. This compares to our SoTP, which values Santander Brazil using a \(14\%\) CoE, or \(7.5x\) P/E. If upcoming elections result in more market- friendly economic policies, we believe there could be upside to both earnings and the multiple. As a reference, if the CoE falls to \(12\%\) and ROTE improves to \(20\%\) , we would see \(7 - 8\%\) upside to our valuation. On the contrary, if we value SAN Brazil at the bottom of the range, \(6.6x\) P/E, our valuation would be reduced to €9.4, just over \(1\%\) .
Santander (PT €9.5, Overweight)

We raise our estimates by \(7 / 8\%\) in 2026/27E. \(40\%\) of the upgrade is driven by the announced TSB acquisition, but we also raise numbers in Spain, Brazil and DCB. Our numbers are \(6 / 9\%\) ahead of consensus in 2026/2027E. Apart from the integration of TSB:

- We raise our earnings \(5\%\) in Brazil. With our economists now expecting rate cuts in the US in September, we believe Brazil could follow, accelerating NII growth to \(8 - 11\%\) in 2026-2028E. We are \(2 - 4\%\) ahead of VA consensus PTP despite assuming a \(10\%\) accumulated depreciation in the BRL vs. the EUR for 2028 vs. 2Q25.

- We incorporate a lower tax rate in Spain. Despite the bank tax now been booked in the tax line, the effective tax rate in Spain appears not to have increased. This seems to be related to Equity income and dividend contribution to the P&L, but Santander also has €11.2bn off-balance sheet DTAs, the majority of which we believe are related to Banco Popular, which could be playing a roll. Company guidance points to a \(30\%\) tax rate for the region as sustainable, which we incorporate. This drives our \(17 - 23\%\) higher net profit vs. consensus in Spain, although we are \(7 - 11\%\) ahead on Ppop as well in 2026-2027E.

- We remove UK Motor Finance related top ups in 2026/27E. We have a final €120mn top up in 4Q25, which will align Santander's coverage to Lloyd's. This compares to the €300mn in 4Q25 and €240mn in 2026E we had previously. Together with the disposal of Poland, we believe this reduces litigation risk materially, and leaves us \(20\%\) above consensus in the DCB division 2026/27E.

With the ROTE at 16.5- 18.5% 2026- 2028E and \(4.6\%\) RWA CAGR, we estimate Santander could afford to pay out \(70\%\) of the earnings. We believe its capital deployment policy will remain largely unchanged. We expect a normalized payout of \(50\%\) , and in the absence of any M&A, we think it could afford a further €3.2bn extraordinary buyback in the 2026E fiscal year (unchanged). However, we add a new €3.5bn buyback in 2027E and 2028E. This would take the total average payout to just over \(70\%\) and keep CET1 at the \(13\%\) level. Our total accumulated distribution out to 2028E reaches just over €40bn, compared to Consensus at €32bn.

We believe M&A is possible (management have said they would consider bolt- on acquisitions). And if it happens, it could be at the expense of extraordinary buybacks; however, with the \(20\%\) ROI hurdle rate management are targeting, this would be positive for valuation, considering we estimate Santander trades at an implied \(14 - 15\%\) CoE.

With the disposal of Poland, re- deployment of capital in the UK, and Motor Finance developments over the summer, all happening within a short period of time, we believe consensus numbers have not yet been properly updated. As the company lays out its plan for 2025- 2028E in February, we see \(6 - 9\%\) upgrades on the cards.

On our above- consensus numbers, the stock trades on \(8.3x\) PE 2026 vs. the sector on \(9.5x\) , with a higher EPS growth at \(13\%\) CAGR 2024- 2027E vs. the sector at \(11\%\) . Our increased total payout of \(70\%\) also puts it at a \(9 - 10\%\) yield vs. the sector on \(8\%\) .

At our new PT of €9.5, the stock would be trading on 1.55x TBV 2026E. We use 12.5% Cost of Equity, and in this note, we roll our valuation over to December 2026E. We believe Brazil's October 2026 elections could reduce the 14% CoE we are using for the region, should more pro-market policies come out of it. Also, if the company addresses US Retail's poor profitability, we see potential for further CoE compression. Combined, we see 10- 15% potential upside to our valuation.

In this note we also update our Bull and Bear scenarios. We reflect the 20% ROTE and CoE compression potential in the Bull case scenario, and we reflect the better profitability and capital starting point in our Bear case, which was somewhat stale.

Brazil remains a source of vulnerability; however, on the \(7.5xP / E\) we use in our valuation, we believe this is priced in, while USD weakness/Fed pivot provides room for optimism in 2026/27E. Santander Brazil is making \(15\%\) ROTE pre- AT1s 1H25 vs. a range of \(14 - 20\%\) the last decade or so. For a franchise that makes most of its money on the lending margin vs. the liability margin, we believe lower rates will be key to restore the historical profitability, together with the global re- platforming initiatives. We forecast \(18\%\) PTP growth in 2025- 28E and the ROTE recovering to the middle of the range at \(17.5\%\) already in 2026E. We are \(4\%\) above consensus on PTP.

The majority of the NII at Santander Brazil is generated by consumer lending and less so by the deposit or liability margin. As a reference, \(78\%\) of the deposits in 2Q25 were Term deposits. Based on our estimates in 2024, the cost of deposits was at \(9.9\%\) vs. an average SELIC rate of just under \(11\%\) , ie the deposit beta was at \(90\%\) . The loan yield, on the other hand, has been at an average \(200\%\) of the SELIC rate in the last decade, or at an average 500bp spread. As rates come down, it will have very little deposit margin to lose, if any, while consumer lending typically sees more inelastic loan yields, and volumes should also accelerate.

At a system level, loan growth has remained resilient, despite the higher Selic rate. We believe this is to do with the fiscal balance and the subsidies to lower income households. In the case of Santander, it has been growing below the market, we believe, due to a combination of de- risking of the book and the refocusing of the business. As we look forward, we would expect the loan growth to accelerate from the current \(5.3\%\) yoy (local accounting) closer to double digit. We forecast \(8\%\) yoy loan growth in 2025, increasing to \(10\%\) in 2027E, and with higher margin we see Nll growing \(8 - 11\%\) in 2026- 28E.

The budget deficit in Brazil is expected to end this year at \(9.2\%\) . Looser fiscal policy was the main reason behind the currency sell- off late last year and the higher inflation expectations are what drove the central bank to hike rates aggressively from a 2024 low of \(10.5\%\) to \(15\%\) .

The budget deficit remains the biggest issue for the economy; however, we believe USD weakness is making the situation more manageable. With a weaker USD, our economists see room for inflation to moderate, which leaves room for Brazil to follow the Fed in cutting rates 1Q26 (our Latam economists' forecast) or earlier (market pricing). Considering interest payments are one of the biggest factors behind the deficit (primary
balance is at - 0.5%), this would alleviate some of the pressure short term.

There are presidential elections in 2026. This means fiscal tightening is unlikely in the short term, and the closer we get to the elections, it is possible volatility will increase. We see the currency as the biggest contagion channel for Santander's groups earnings, and with the rate differential still so high, we believe it is unlikely the currency would materially depreciate. In our forecasts, we incorporate a depreciation of the BRL vs. the EUR of 5% in 2025, 4% in 2026 and 3% from thereon, acknowledging the inflation differential is narrowing, based on MS estimates.

The US posted an 11.6% ROTE in 1H25, and remains the least profitable region within the group. The business that is dragging the regional profitability down is the legacy of the Sovereign bank acquisition in 2010, and in particular the retail operations. Looking at the local 10Q accounts, as well as cross- referencing the consumer division breakdown and the country breakdown, we conclude that US Retail banking operations are barely break- even, or possibly posting a small loss. Excluding this business, the US would have a C/I ratio over 10 percentage points lower and the group C/I ratio would improve by c. 14Obp. With Openbank now up and running in the US, and management noting that some of the regulatory impediments to integrating the businesses have cleared, we believe more decisive action is now possible.

Santander's US operations are made up of several businesses, the largest of which is the profitable US Consumer bank. In addition to that, it has the traditional Retail and Commercial operations that originated from the acquisition of Sovereign Bank in 2010. And more recently, it is building out CIB capabilities to leverage its global presence in the US, including the hiring of a number of ex- Credit Suisse bankers, and the acquisition of Amherst Pierpont in 2021. Finally it also has a well functioning and profitable private bank in Miami.

The profitability drag is in the Retail operations most of all. Sovereign was a struggling US regional bank, poorly managed, which suffered in the aftermath of the GFC. Since then, Santander has tried to revamp the franchise, but 15 years later, this has not proven successful. Looking at the 1H25 10Q, the C/I of the Retail operations is at 87%, pre allocation of corporate center costs, vs. the average in the US of 57%, using local accounting, and the average of the group at 41% 2025E.

Santander doesn't disclose the equity by business, but we have allocated it pro- rata by assets which are disclosed, and we have also allocated costs and revenues from central items proportionally. Based on this, we estimate the operations of the Old Sovereign combined have an 81% C/I ratio (see Exhibit 26), and we believe the retail standalone segment is likely loss making including Openbank US.

Based on local accounting, we estimate the business has c. 3bn allocated capital with 26bn of RWAs. Excluding both revenues and costs from US Retail and Commercial from the group, and reducing the RWAs by that amount, we estimate the C/I ratio of the group would improve by 140bp, and the CET1 would increase by c. 60bp. The estimated ROTE on a 13% CET1 (our go to CET1) would then increase by 130bp.

Management have made it clear that their strategy in the US is organic, and we would not speculate on any disposal; however, there are other levers it can pull. Although the US Consumer bank has been integrated into the US holding company for some time now, the company has explained that regulatory restrictions were in place that prevented a significant integration and cost takeout until now. We believe this, together with the fact that Openbank has now been launched, opens the door to more decisive action to improve profitability in the division. Options now permitted that could generate significant cost savings would include potentially running off the business or a much tighter integration with Openbank. We do not include any of these options in our base case, but acknowledge that potential for higher earnings and simplification of the business would also carry a lower CoE.
